Abstract.

Unstable pressure and u-equilibrium states are introduced and investigated for a partially hyperbolic diffeomorphsim fğ‘“f. We define the u-pressure Puâ€‹(f,Ï†)superscriptğ‘ƒğ‘¢ğ‘“ğœ‘P^{u}(f,\varphi) of fğ‘“f at a continuous function Ï†ğœ‘\varphi via the dynamics of fğ‘“f on local unstable leaves. A variational principle for unstable pressure Puâ€‹(f,Ï†)superscriptğ‘ƒğ‘¢ğ‘“ğœ‘P^{u}(f,\varphi), which states that Puâ€‹(f,Ï†)superscriptğ‘ƒğ‘¢ğ‘“ğœ‘P^{u}(f,\varphi) is the supremum of the sum of the unstable entropy and the integral of Ï†ğœ‘\varphi taken over all invariant measures, is obtained. U-equilibrium states at which the supremum in the variational principle attains and their relation to Gibbs u-states are studied. Differentiability properties of unstable pressure, such as tangent functionals, Gateaux differentiability and FrÃ©chet differentiability and their relations to u-equilibrium states, are also considered.

0. Introduction

Entropy and pressure are important invariants in the study of dynamical systems and ergodic theory. Entropies, including topological entropy and measure-theoretic entropy, are measurements of complexity of the orbit structure of the system from different points of view. As a generalization of entropy, the concept of pressure was introduced by Ruelle [15] and studied in the general case in Walters [16]. In fact, the theory of pressure and its related topics, such as Gibbs measures and equilibrium states, are the main constituent components of the mathematical statistical mechanics.

Let fğ‘“f be a C1+Î±superscriptğ¶1ğ›¼C^{1+\alpha}-diffeomorphism on a closed Riemannian manifold Mğ‘€M where Î±>0ğ›¼0\alpha>0. The well-known entropy formula in [11] shows that if Î¼ğœ‡\mu is an SRB measure, then the corresponding metric entropy hÎ¼â€‹(f)subscriptâ„ğœ‡ğ‘“h_{\mu}(f) is the integration of the summation of the positive Lyapunov exponents. It tells us that positive exponents have contribution to the metric entropy. In particular, when fğ‘“f is uniformly hyperbolic, both of the metric entropy and topological entropy are caused by the dynamics on the unstable foliations. However, when fğ‘“f is (uniformly) partially hyperbolic, things become delicate. The presence of the center direction makes the dynamics much more complicated.

Recent years, the entropy theory for partially hyperbolic diffeomorphisms are increasingly investigated. We can see the progress in this research topic in [7], [19], [20], [6], etc. In particular, for any C1superscriptğ¶1C^{1}-partially hyperbolic diffeomorphism fğ‘“f, Hu, Hua and Wu [6] introduce the definitions of unstable metric entropy hÎ¼uâ€‹(f)subscriptsuperscriptâ„ğ‘¢ğœ‡ğ‘“h^{u}_{\mu}(f) for any invariant measure Î¼ğœ‡\mu and unstable topological entropy htopuâ€‹(f)superscriptsubscriptâ„topğ‘¢ğ‘“h_{\text{top}}^{u}(f). Precisely, hÎ¼uâ€‹(f)subscriptsuperscriptâ„ğ‘¢ğœ‡ğ‘“h^{u}_{\mu}(f) is defined by using HÎ¼â€‹(â‹i=0nâˆ’1fâˆ’iâ€‹Î±|Î·)subscriptğ»ğœ‡conditionalsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘–0ğ‘›1superscriptğ‘“ğ‘–ğ›¼ğœ‚H_{\mu}(\bigvee_{i=0}^{n-1}f^{-i}\alpha|\eta), where Î±ğ›¼\alpha is a finite measurable partition, and Î·ğœ‚\eta is a measurable partition subordinate to unstable manifolds that can be obtained by refining a finite partition into pieces of unstable leaves; htopuâ€‹(f)superscriptsubscriptâ„topğ‘¢ğ‘“h_{\text{top}}^{u}(f) is defined by the topological entropy of fğ‘“f on local unstable manifolds. Similar to that in the classical entropy theory, the corresponding versions of Shannon-McMillan-Breiman theorem and local entropy formula for hÎ¼uâ€‹(f)subscriptsuperscriptâ„ğ‘¢ğœ‡ğ‘“h^{u}_{\mu}(f), and the variational principle relating hÎ¼uâ€‹(f)subscriptsuperscriptâ„ğ‘¢ğœ‡ğ‘“h^{u}_{\mu}(f) and htopuâ€‹(f)superscriptsubscriptâ„topğ‘¢ğ‘“h_{\text{top}}^{u}(f) are given. The main feature of these unstable entropies is to rule out the complexity caused by the center directions and focus on that caused by the unstable directions. In fact, hÎ¼uâ€‹(f)subscriptsuperscriptâ„ğ‘¢ğœ‡ğ‘“h^{u}_{\mu}(f) is equal to hÎ¼â€‹(f,Î¾):=HÎ¼â€‹(Î¾|fâ€‹Î¾)assignsubscriptâ„ğœ‡ğ‘“ğœ‰subscriptğ»ğœ‡conditionalğœ‰ğ‘“ğœ‰h_{\mu}(f,\xi):=H_{\mu}(\xi|f\xi) (where Î¾ğœ‰\xi is an increasing partition subordinate to the unstable leaves) which was introduced by Ledrappier and Young [11]. Comparing the above two types of definition for the unstable metric entropy, we can see that the former one is more natural and easy-to-understand than the latter one.

The main purpose of this paper is to introduce unstable topological pressure Puâ€‹(f,Ï†)superscriptğ‘ƒğ‘¢ğ‘“ğœ‘P^{u}(f,\varphi) for a C1superscriptğ¶1C^{1}-partially hyperbolic diffeomorphism f:Mâ†’M:ğ‘“â†’ğ‘€ğ‘€f:M\to M and any continuous function Ï†ğœ‘\varphi on Mğ‘€M, obtain a variational principle for this pressure, and investigate the corresponding so-called u-equilibriums.

It is well known that the variational principle for the classical pressure was first given by Ruelle [15] for the system with the expansiveness and specification assumptions and then was obtained by Walters [17] for the general case. It shows that

The measure at which the supremum attains in the variational principle for unstable pressure Puâ€‹(f,Ï†)superscriptğ‘ƒğ‘¢ğ‘“ğœ‘P^{u}(f,\varphi) is called a u-equilibrium state for fğ‘“f at Ï†ğœ‘\varphi (see Definition 1.4). Some fundamental properties for the set of u-equilibrium states are considered (Theorem B). Among these properties, we show that there always exists a u-equilibrium state for a C1superscriptğ¶1C^{1}-partially hyperbolic diffeomorphism, in contrast to the case for the classical equilibrium state. This is essentially due to the upper semi-continuity of the unstable entropy map Î¼â†¦hÎ¼uâ€‹(f)maps-toğœ‡subscriptsuperscriptâ„ğ‘¢ğœ‡ğ‘“\mu\mapsto h^{u}_{\mu}(f). In [17] and [18], some properties about the classical pressure and equilibrium states were investigated. We can consider the corresponding properties for unstable pressure and u-equilibrium states. We show that unstable pressure determines invariant measures (Theorem D) and there is a close relation between u-equilibrium states and tangent functionals (Theorem E). To study the uniqueness of u-equilibrium state, we define two types, Gateaux type and FrechÃ©t type, of differentiability of unstable pressure of fğ‘“f at Ï†ğœ‘\varphi, and obtain several properties of them (Theorems F and G).

The paper is organized as follows. In Section 1, we give the definitions of unstable pressure and u-equilibrium state, and formulate the main results. We provide some properties of unstable pressure in Section 2. Section 3 is for the proof of the variational principle of unstable pressure. In Section 4 and 5, we consider the properties of u-equilibrium states and study how does the unstable pressure determine invariant measures. In Section 6, differentiability properties of unstable pressure are investigated.
